\begin{align*}
a_1q^4 - a_1q^3 &= 576,\\
a_1q - a_1 &= 9.
\end{align*}
<answer>From the first two equations, we can deduce the value of $q$, which is $q = 1 + \frac{1}{3}$ or $q = 1 - \frac{1}{3}$. Since the terms are positive, we take $q = \frac{4}{3}$. Using the second equation, we find $a_1 = 3$. Therefore, the sum of the first five terms is $a_1(1 + q + q^2 + q^3 + q^4) = 3(1 + \frac{4}{3} + \frac{16}{9} + \frac{64}{27} + \frac{256}{81}) = \boxed{\frac{31}{3}}.$</answer>

Let $x$ be the distance between the elephant and the lion at any time  $t$. Then $x(0) = 1.$ The elephant and the lion each i...</think>
<answer>Because both the elephant and the lion are running at constant speed, we can assume that their positions as functions of time, $p_E(t)$ and $p_L(t)$, are linear functions. We also assume that
\begin{align*}
p_E(0) &= 0, \\
p_E(x) &= 19x, \\
p_L(x) &= 24x,
\end{align*}
where $x$ is the distance between the two animals in miles and $p_E(x)$ and $p_E(x)$ are their position in miles as functions of time. Then the distance between the two animals as an function of time, $p(x)(t)$, is
\begin{align*}
p(x)(0) &= 1, \\
p(x)(x) &= -p_E(x)(x) + p_L(x)(x) = 24x - 19x,
\end{align*}
so $p(x)(t) = 24 - 19x$. We can then set this equal to $0$ and show that it takes the lion $1$ hour to catch the elephant...</answer>

